Switch to using a virtual sensor (gerrit 75563) and modify the fan table accordingly.

This modification is dependent on 
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/72455
https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/openbmc/+/72454
It is for determining the current status of the slot when performing slot hot service.

Since the Thermal team stated on August 6th that there will be no Air blocker in the data center in the future, the changes made in https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/openbmc/+/72454
and https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/72455
to determine the presence of an Air blocker are no longer needed. 

Instead, it is sufficient to determine if the Sentinel Dome is inserted into the slot based on the Fru object under the Entity manager
Acknowledged
Why are we stopping the fan control service??

Because I don't want the fan speed to be readjusted by the phosphor-pid-control's auto mode after I adjust the fan duty.

Or is it that I don't actually need to stop the phosphor-pid control?
I just need to use `busctl` to set the `Manual` property under `/xyz/openbmc_project/settings/fanctrl/zone0` to `true`, then adjust the fan duty. 
When I need to return to auto mode, I can set the `Manual` property back to `false`?
Yes, please use manual mode if that's what you need.

I found that if I don't stop the fan control service, even if it is set to manual mode (`Manual` property set to true), the fan speed will still be overridden and the `Manual` property will be set to false.

This might be because the object paths related to `Sentinel Dome` under the `Entity Manager` change after slot plug in and unplug.
When the fan control service detects the new configuration, it starts the `tryRestartControlLoops`. 
Within `tryRestartControlLoops`, the `buildZones` function is called, which creates the `DbusPidZone` object and initializes the `_manualMode` property to false.

Therefore, I still stop the fan control service.
Otherwise, after setting the fan speed in manual mode, the fan control will reload the configuration successfully and run in auto mode after about 20 seconds.

Should I not stop the fan control service in this case?
Instead, should the fan control service check if it was set to manual mode before reloading the configuration and then initialize the DbusPidZone accordingly?

Thank you very much.
You cannot make calls to a facebook/openbmc tool in the open source code.

How about using `busctl` to set the `Target` property of the `xyz.openbmc_project.FanSensor` object under the `xyz.openbmc_project.FanSensor` service to the corresponding value to adjust the fan speed?
Is this method correct?

Thank you for your suggestion.
Yes.
All fan control operations have been switched to using `busctl` instead of `mfg-tool`.
I'm unwilling to maintain all of this state in shell scripts.  We need to find something more robust than this.

Do you mean that this should be implemented within the `phosphor-pid-control`?
To support the service window, we need to be able to distinguish that the sensors on the Server board do not need to be monitored when the Server board is unplugged, rather than considering them as sensor failures.

Thank you very much.

Apologies, let me correct that.
Under the dynamic fan table, the sensors on the Server Board will not be monitored after it is unplugged.
Instead, it is necessary to know the total number of Server Boards in the system to determine if the Service window conditions are met.
Done
Why are we still stopping phosphor-pid-control?  We already set the fans for that fan control board to manual mode, but now what happens to the *other board*??

I am still stopping the phosphor-pid-control because I found that if I don’t stop the fan control service, even if it is set to manual mode (Manual property set to true), the fan speed will still be overridden and the Manual property will be set to false.


This might be because the object paths related to `Sentinel Dome` under the `Entity Manager` change after slot plug in and unplug.
When the fan control service detects the new configuration, it starts the `tryRestartControlLoops`. 
Within `tryRestartControlLoops`, the `buildZones` function is called, which creates the `DbusPidZone` object and initializes the `_manualMode` property to false.


Therefore, I still stop the fan control service. Otherwise, after setting the fan speed in manual mode, the fan control will reload the configuration successfully and run in auto mode after about 20 seconds.


Should I not stop the fan control service in this case?
Instead, should the fan control service check if it was set to manual mode before reloading the configuration and then initialize the `DbusPidZone` accordingly?


Did I misunderstand anything?
Thank you very much.

I will first look into how to make `phosphor-pid-control` check if it was set to manual mode before reloading the configuration, so that I can implement the Service window function without stopping `phosphor-pid-control`.

The part that stops phosphor-pid-control has been removed and replaced with fan duty control using manual mode and auto mode.  

Additionally, regarding the issue where manual mode was unexpectedly switched back to auto mode, I have made changes to phosphor-pid-control in Gerrit: https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-pid-control/+/74780
I will contact the reviewer for review.
Why is it zone0?  What happens to the other board?

In the current `Yosemite4` system, both fan boards and all temperature sensors in the system are managed together in the same zone.
Therefore, the phosphor-pid-control will control both fan board0 and fan board1 simultaneously.
Done
The merge conflict has been resolved.
Changing the machine's "manual mode" automatically through shell scripts is not a very robust method to handle this problem.  We need to come up with a less error prone and easier to maintain design.

Should we implement the handling of the service window and HSC fault as separate D-Bus methods in phosphor-pid-control?

The current idea is to allow users to enable/disable these functions and define their parameters:

1. Handle Service Window Method:
At startup, phosphor-pid-control will check the user’s defined service window speed and conditions.
Based on these definitions, it will decide whether to adjust to the target speed without activating auto mode.
During runtime, users can define which GPIO pin changes should trigger a service window check by gpio-monitor.
When such a change is detected, the handle service window method will be called to adjust the fan speed accordingly.

2. Handle HSC Fault:
During runtime, using a signal handler, the fan speed will be adjusted to the target speed upon receiving a user-specified signal.

Thank you for your guidance.
